## Contemporary Political Corruption in the United States

### Current Perceptions and Rankings

Despite historical progress, political corruption remains a significant concern in the U.S. Transparency International’s Corruption Perceptions Index (CPI) is a widely respected measure of perceived public sector corruption worldwide. The U.S. scored 67 out of 100 in 2021, ranking 27th out of 180 countries. This represents a decline from previous years, such as 2016 when the U.S. ranked 18th, and 2017 when it ranked 16th with a score of 71 ([Transparency International, 2021](https://www.transparency.org/en/countries/united-states)).

| Year | CPI Score (0=highly corrupt, 100=very clean) | Global Rank (out of 180) |
|-------|----------------------------------------------|--------------------------|
| 2016  | 71                                           | 18                       |
| 2017  | 71                                           | 16                       |
| 2021  | 67                                           | 27                       |

This downward trend signals growing concerns about corruption and governance in the U.S.

### Public Opinion and Trust

Public opinion surveys reinforce the perception that corruption is worsening. The 2017 U.S. Corruption Barometer by Transparency International found:

- Nearly 60% of Americans believed corruption had increased in the previous year, up from about 33% in 2016.
- 44% perceived corruption as pervasive in the White House, an increase from 36% in 2016.
- Almost 70% believed the government was failing to combat corruption effectively.
- Fear of retaliation was cited by 55% as the main reason people hesitate to report corruption, a significant rise from 31% in 2016 ([Transparency International, 2017](https://www.transparency.org/en/news/corruption-in-the-usa-the-difference-a-year-makes)).

These figures indicate a growing distrust in political institutions and a perception that corruption is entrenched at high levels of government.

### Forms and Manifestations of Corruption

Political corruption in the U.S. today manifests in various forms:

- **Influence of Wealthy Individuals and Corporations:** The role of money in politics, including “pay-to-play” politics, lobbying, and campaign finance, is a major concern. Despite legal regulations, large sums of money flow into political campaigns, often creating expectations of reciprocal favors ([EssayBasics, 2017](https://blog.essaybasics.com/corruption-in-politics-essay-sample/)).
  
- **Revolving Doors:** The movement of individuals between government positions and private sector roles, especially in industries they once regulated, raises conflicts of interest.

- **Abuse of the Financial System:** The U.S. financial system has been exploited by corrupt foreign kleptocrats and local elites to launder money and hide illicit wealth, with the U.S. ranked second in the Financial Secrecy Index behind the Cayman Islands ([Wikipedia, 2023](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corruption_in_the_United_States)).

- **Public Integrity Offenses:** Bribery, embezzlement, and other “traditional” corruption forms still occur, though less frequently than in the past. The Department of Justice maintains a division focused on public integrity offenses ([Stephenson, 2020](https://today.law.harvard.edu/a-history-of-corruption-in-the-united-states/)).

- **Political Polarization and Ethical Norms:** Transparency International has highlighted an erosion of ethical norms at the highest levels of power, exacerbated by populism, nativism, and political polarization, which threaten the system of checks and balances ([Transparency International, 2019](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corruption_in_the_United_States)).

